@node "OtherPrgs" "Other programs!"

   @{MS "Other programs!"}
   @{MS "BoulderDäsh   [game/jump/boulderdaesh.lha]"}

Clone of the original Boulderdäsh for Amiga. It is the only version running faster on Amiga than the
original. It looks and behaves like the original. I was asked, where the C64 is. (-8 And all this on
a 68000 without Fastmem.

   @{MS "SimpleCat   [dev/misc/simplecat.lha]"}

This tool is for programmers and user. Using this program you can change catalogs of programs with
your favourite text editor in the easiest way. These programs must include a CS file. Search for it
in the archive of the catalogs drawer.

   @{MS "Afind   [util/misc/afind.lha]"}

With this program you can search for programs on your Aminet CDs in the easiest way. It is the same
than the original tool on the CD, but here you can use AminetCDs and AminetSets mixed. So you are
not forced to search for a program on the first 5 Aminet CDs, that is on AminetSet1 Disc b.

   @{MS "AView   [util/misc/aview.lha]"}

AView is a great multiview enhancement/replacement! It is working like Multiview, but you are able
to specify a special viewer/player for each file type.

   @{MS "Guideformat   [text/edit/guideformat.lha]"}

GuideFormat is a simple tool. It is easy to format text blocks, even if there are "links" or other
guide commands in.

   @{MS "GuideCheck   [text/edit/guidecheck.lha]"}

GuideCheck is a tool, that allows to check an entire guide file and discovers all errors!

   @{MS "SiedlerBoot   [game/patch/siedlerboot.lha]"}

This allows to start the Settlers direct via CD and save the scores on HD. There is no hard disc
install required. SiedlerBoot requires the "Amiga Plus Sonderheft 9" cover CDROM.

   @{MS "Execute64   [misc/emu/execute64.lha]"}

Execute64 allows to transfer file direct into the C64 and to start them. This allows to play games
an use the Amiga a big file server.

   @{MS "R   [util/cli/r.lha]"}

"R" creates a GUI for each DOS Program. This allows you to use DOS commands even if you aren't very
good in reading templates.

   @{MS "DVBControl   [comm/misc/dvbcontrol.lha]"}

DVBControl is a software project for the Nokia MediaMaster (D-Box) and DVB2000 firmware. It allows
to update firmware, edit channel settings and much more. So if you are using DVB2000 and an Amiga
DVBcontrol is your only choice!

   @{MS "MCControl   [hard/hack/mccontrol.lha]"}

MCControl (MemoryCard Control) is a card reader for Playstation MemoryCards. It requires a little
self made hardware (~$5) and the free software!

   @{MS "VBRControl   [util/sys/vbrcontrol.lha]"}

VBRControl moves the processor vector base to fast ram. This is increasing system speed.

   @{MS "AvailCPU   [util/sys/availcpu.lha]"}

AvailCPU is a little program that shows the CPU usage by using the Power LED!

   @{MS "TrackDisplayClock   [util/time/trackdisplaycl.lha]"}

A hardware track display is very useful, if you need it! The most time this type of hardware is only
good for lighting up the room! This will be changed when using TrackDisplayClock! TrackDisplayClock
displays the system time on your track display! Its cool, its useful and of cource the time is
always in visual range. Delete all programs using screens, windows or icons to display the time and
of course don't forget to remove your noclick tool! TrackDisplayClock is doing all these jobs and
your system will be faster than before! (-8

   @{MS "MMKeyboard   [hard/hack/MMKeyboard.lha]"}

MMKeyboard is a hardware for using IBM-PC keyboards on Amiga. It allows to use multimedia keys like
Play or Pause. MMKeyboard supports any key on any keyboard! No special driver for each keyboard like
on the PC! Only one small commodity for all keyboards is required to smuggle the multimedia keys
into the system. MMKeyboard is full reset handler compatible, contains a internal hardware password,
allows to turn your Amiga on and off by using the keyboard and much more.

   @{MS "ParKeyboard   [hard/hack/ParKeyboard.lha]"}

ParKeyboard is a small hard and software project that allows you to use an Amiga keyboard connected
to the parallel port. The interface did't contain any components. Just four wires are required to
adapt the parallel port.

   @{MS "WheelMouseSupport  [util/mouse/WheelMouseSupp.lha]"}

WheelMouseSupport is a WheelBusMouse Software replacement. It allows to use the mouse wheel with most
Amiga programs without any patches.

@endnode

@node "Technical" "Technical information about AView"

@{MS "Technical information about AView"}

AView is 100% assembler coded.@{par}

The sourcecode takes 298042 bytes in 54 files. AView is assembled with DevPac 3.04. DevPac needs 4
seconds and 755150 KB each time.@{par}

AView was programmed on an A2000-030/25Mhz (32 MEG).@{par}

I wrote this guide using GoldEd (3.x/4.x) and his fantastic fold features together with
@{"GuideCheck" link "OtherPrgs"}.@{par}

@endnode

@node "COMMAND" "The File Identification Commands"

@{MS "The File Identification Commands"}

The @{"identifier" link "EditIden"} gadget allows to define own file types, by using the following
commands.

@{MS "GENERAL"}

All commands must be separated by one space as minimum.@{par}

Command names are case insensitiv. "@{"MATCH" link "CO_MATCH" }" = "MaTcH"@{par}

All commands are only scanning the fist 8 KB buffer of a file. If a command is reading beyond this
8KB the hole file type fails. A file size which is smaller than 8KB will be handled like a smaller
buffer.

@{MS "A List Of All Commands"}

   @{" " link "CO_MATCH" } MATCH        Check specified Bytes or Strings@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_FIND" } FIND         Search for Bytes or Strings@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_NAME" } NAME         Check file name@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_FILESIZE" } FILESIZE     Check file size@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_ASCII" } ASCII        Check for ASCII file@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_BINARY" } BINARY        Check for BINARY file@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_AND" } AND          AND-operation@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_OR" } OR           OR-operation@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_NOT" } NOT          NOT-operation@{par}
   @{" " link "CO_BRACKET" } ()           Bracket operation@{par}
@endnode
@node "CO_MATCH" "Command: MATCH"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "Match"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

MATCH [Offset/N,] String@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command allows to check bytes or strings starting on a direct offset.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

MATCH "Hello"@{par}

Checks for a "Hello" in the first 5 bytes of a file.@{par}

MATCH 1,"Hallo"@{par}

Checks for a "Hello". This time the offset is one.@{par}

MATCH 27,$1234@{par}

This match is looking for a $1234 on file offset 27.@{par}

MATCH 0,"FORM????ILBM"@{par}

This detects a "FORM" on offset zero and an "ILBM" on offset eight. A "?" means no further check.
This Byte will be skipped.@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

The offset is optional and always zero if not specified.@{par}

The offset is always decimal.@{par}

The String must start with an " or a $!@{par}

The String may contain "?". This bytes won´t be checked.@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_FIND" "Command: FIND"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "FIND"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

FIND [Start/N,] [End/N,] String@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command allows to search for a string between two offsets.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

FIND "Hello"@{par}

AView is searching the whole buffer! The search pattern is "Hello".@{par}

FIND 10,"Smurf"@{par}

AView is searching the string "Smurf" between 0 and 10.@{par}

FIND 1,10,"Smurf"@{par}

AView is searching for the string "Smurf" between 1 and 10. 10 is the last offset. This means AView
will search the last time by using offset 10: "S" on offset 10, "m" on offset 11 and so on.@{par}

FIND 1,127,$0001@{par}

AView is searching for the bytes $00 and $01 between "1" and "127".@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

The offsets are optional. If only one is specified this is the search end. If nothing is declared
the whole buffer will be searched.@{par}

Both offsets are decimal.@{par}

The String must start with an " or a $!@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_NAME" "Command: NAME"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "NAME"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

NAME Pattern/N@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command compares the file name by using dos pattern.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

NAME "#?.gif"@{par}

This command will be only successful on files like "Smurf.gif"!@{par}

NAME "#?.(jpeg|jpg)"@{par}

Only file names with .jpeg or .jpg at the end are valid.@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

The pattern must be enclosed with "!@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_FILESIZE" "Command: FILESIZE"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "FILESIZE"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

FILESIZE Number/N@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command compares the file size and the declared number.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}@{par}

FILESIZE 901120@{par}

This command only comes true if the file size is equal to the specified number.@{par}

FILESIZE 1024 @{"AND" link "CO_AND"} @{"NAME" link "CO_NAME"} "BootBlock#?"@{par}

This file size must be 1024 and the file name must start with "BootBlock".@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

The number must be decimal.@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_ASCII" "Command ASCII"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "ASCII"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

ASCII@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command checks for non ASCII Bytes and will return "1" on the condition that there is non.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

ASCII@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

The @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII"} and the @{"BINARY" link "CO_BINARY"} command are switched to a
special mode, if specified first within the identifier gadget.@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_BINARY" "Command BINARY"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "BINARY"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

BINARY@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command checks for BINARY Bytes and will return "1" on the condition that there is one.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

BINARY@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

The @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII"} and the BINARY command are switched to a special mode, if specified
first within the identifier gadget.@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_AND" "Command: AND"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "AND"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

AND@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command allows to connect @{"commands" link "COMMAND"} via an AND operation.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME"} "#?.txt" AND @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" }@{par}

This will be successful if the name ends with a ".txt" @{b}and@{ub} it is
an @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII"} file.@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME"} "#?.txt" & @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" }@{par}

This is equal to the last example.@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME"} "#?.guide" & @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" } AND @{"FIND" link "CO_FIND" }
40,"\@Database"@{par}

The file name must end with a ".guide" and the file must contain an "\@Database" starting within the
first 40 bytes.@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

You are allowed to use the short version of AND: "&"@{par}

An AND operation is always solved before an @{"Or" link "CO_OR"} operation. It is possible to
override this by using @{"Brackets" link "CO_Bracket"}@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_OR" "Command: OR"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "OR"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

OR@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command allows to connect @{"single commands" link "COMMAND"} with an OR operation.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.txt" OR @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" }@{par}

The @{"NAME" link "CO_NAME"} must end with ".txt" or the file mast be an @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII"}
text to succeed this identifier.@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.txt" | @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" }@{par}

This example is equal to the first one.@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.guide" | @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" } OR @{"FIND" link "CO_FIND" }
40,"\@Database"@{par}

One of the three commands must succeed to make this file identification successful.@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

"|" is the short version of "OR"@{par}

An @{"AND" link "CO_AND"} operation has a higher priority. The only way to change this priority is
to use @{"Brackets" link "CO_BRACKET"}.@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_NOT" "Command: NOT"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "NOT"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

NOT@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

This command causes a negation.@{par}

@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.hft" @{"AND" link "CO_AND"} NOT @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" }@{par}

This line will check for a file that is not @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII"}. Additional to that the file
name must end with a ".hft".@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.hft" @{"AND" link "CO_AND"} ~ @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" }@{par}

This example is equal to the first one.@{par}

~ (@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.data" & @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" })@{par}

No ".data" and no @{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII"} file.@{par}

@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

"~" is the short version of "NOT"@{par}

A NOT operations is always prefered. The only exception are @{"brackets" link "CO_BRACKET" }. =>
"NOT NAME "Hello" AND ASCII" = "(NOT NAME "Hello) AND ASCII"@{par}

@endnode
@node "CO_BRACKET" "COMMAND: ()"
@toc "COMMAND"

@{MS "( and )"}

@{b}TEMPLATE:@{ub}@{par}

(@{par}
)@{par}

@{b}SHORT:@{ub}@{par}

Brackets allow to prefer operations.@{par}


@{b}EXAMPLES:@{ub}@{par}

@{"NAME" link "CO_NAME" } "#?.guide" @{"AND" link "CO_AND" } (@{"ASCII" link "CO_ASCII" } @{"OR" link "CO_OR" } @{"FIND" link "CO_FIND" } 40,"\@Database")@{par}

File name must end with ".guide". Also an ASCII or a "\@Database" within the first 40 bytes is
required, to succeed this file type.@{par}

This example is the equal to "a*(b+b)"@{par}


@{b}IMPORTANT:@{ub}@{par}

Make sure that all brackets are closed. A missing bracket causes the file type to fail.@{par}

File types are always solved inside out!@{par}

@endnode

@node "PATTNAME" "Pattern: Name/M"
@toc "AView"

@{MS "Name/M"}

"Name" defines the name of the file you want to view. The "/M" means that AView is able to process
as much filenames as possible. Every file name is able to handle DOS pattern matching : E.G "#?.gif"@{par}

Examples:@{par}

AView #?.gif@{par}

AView Smurf.jpg PapaSchlumpf.gif #?smurf#?@{par}

You are allowed to specify a path as well:@{par}

AView sys:pictures/smurfs/Papa.gif sys:Pictures/old/A500.pic@{par}

There are no limits.@{par}

@endnode
@node "PATTALL" "Pattern: All/S"
@toc "AView"

@{MS "All/S"}

"All" allows to scan all sub directories.

@endnode
@node "PATTARG" "Pattern: ARG=To=From/K"
@toc "AView"

@{MS "ARG=To=From/K"}

"ARG", "To" or "From" are very useful. This element will replace the @{"%a" link "EditPreD"}
string.@{par}

For example "lha":@{par}

"LHA x -M -X %n %a"@{par}

@{"%n" link "EditComm"} will be replaced by the name specified with the @{"name" link "PATTNAME"}
pattern. @{"%a" link "EditPreD"} is normally replaced by "t:". This means AView is. decrunching a
lha file to "T:".@{par}

You are able to specify the @{"default %a" link "EditPreD"} argument separately for each file type.@{par}

So "AView Dummy.lha ARG ram:" will decrunch the file "Dummy.lha" direct to "ram:".@{par}

@{b}Important: To use this %a mode one of the following key words is required: ARG, To or From@{ub}@{par}

Examples:@{par}

@{b}AView BoulderDäsh.lha to ram:@{ub}@{par}

This example will decrunch the archive "BoulderDäsh.lha" to "ram:"@{par}

@{b}AView BoulderDäsh.lha from ram:@{ub}@{par}

The result of this example is exact like the first. It looks stupid, because we decrunch to "RAM:"
and not from!@{par}

@endnode
@node "PATTSC" "Pattern: SetComment=SC/S"
@toc "AView"

@{MS "SetComment=SC/S"}

"SetComment" or "SC" is switching AView into the marking mode. All files will be scanned and the
result will be written into the file comment.@{par}

@{b}AView is not able to start any commands during this mode!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PATTSD" "Pattern: ShowDetect=SD/S"
@toc "AView"

@{MS "ShowDetect=SD/S"}

"ShowDetect" or "SD" is viewing the file type of any file.@{par}

@{b}AView is not able to start any commands during this mode!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "PATTDEBUG" "Pattern: Debug/S"
@toc "AView"

@{MS "Debug/S"}

"Debug" shows any problems during file identification. This switch is not useful for normal users.
At this moment AView is only able to view unknown commands and syntax errors.

@endnode

@node "APMa" "The AView preferences"

@{MS "The AView Preferences"}

The AView preferences program allows to modify all file types and the action behind. AViewPrefs
supports @{"menu" link "Menu"} functions as well.@{par}

@{code}
   @{" " link "APMaSoby"}  Sort by
   @{" " link "APMaName"}  Name
   @{" " link "APMaSele"}  Select
   @{" " link "APMaDele"}  Delete
   @{" " link "APMaAlll"}  All
   @{" " link "APMaNeww"}  New
   @{" " link "APMaSave"}  Save
   @{" " link "APMaOkOk"}  Use
   @{" " link "APMaCanc"}  Abort
@endnode
@node "APMaSoBy" "The AView preferences - Sort by"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Sort by"}

@{b}This Gadget is only available during @{"expert mode" link "SETTExpe"}@{ub}@{par}

This gadget allows to sort all entries by name or sub class. Under normal conditions all entries are
sorted by name.@{par}

AView is processing all entries by @{"sub class" link "EditSubC"}.@{par}

If you have created own file types, sorting all entries by @{"sub class" link "EditSubC"} is useful
to find problems.@{par}

@endnode
@node "APMaName" "The AView preferences - Name"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Name"}

This list contains all file types AView is able to detect. Use @{"select" link "APMaSele"} and if
needed @{"New" link "APMaNeww"} to define new entries.@{par}

You are able to scroll via cursor keys. Return or double clicking on one entry opens the
@{"edit" link "Edit"} window.@{par}

@endnode
@node "APMaSele" "The AView preferences - Select"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Select"}

This gadget opens a @{"select" link "GeLw"} window. It allows to select one of the pre defined
identifier.

@endnode
@node "APMaDele" "The AView preferences - Delete"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Delete"}

This gadget deletes the actual identifier.

@endnode
@node "APMaAlll" "The AView preferences - All"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "All"}

All pre defined file types will be added to your prefs list.@{par}

Already existing entries won´t be modified.

@endnode
@node "APMaNeww" "The AView preferences - New"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "New"}

@{b}This Gadget is only available during @{"expert mode" link "SETTExpe"}@{ub}@{par}

You are able to define complete new entries (file types). Just enter a name and AViewPrefs will add
your entry to the list.

@endnode
@node "APMaSave" "The AView preferences - Save"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Save"}

This adjustments will be saved and the requester will be existed.
@endnode
@node "APMaOkOk" "The AView preferences - Use"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Use"}

All adjustments will be used.
@endnode
@node "APMaCanc" "The AView preferences - Abort"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "Abort"}

Cancels all adjustments and quit requester.
@endnode

@node "Edit" "The Edit Window"
@toc "APMa"

@{MS "The Edit Window"}

This window allows all adjustments of the file types.
@{code}

   @{" " link "EditName"}  Name
   @{" " link "EditClas"}  Class
   @{" " link "EditSubC"}  Sub Class
   @{" " link "EditExTy"}  Exec type
   @{" " link "EditStac"}  Stack
   @{" " link "EditComm"}  Command
   @{" " link "EditCuTy"}  Current Type
   @{" " link "EditCuDi"}  Current Directory
   @{" " link "EditWBOu"}  WB Output File
   @{" " link "EditCLIO"}  CLI Output File
   @{" " link "EditIden"}  Identifier
   @{" " link "EditPreD"}  Default %a
   @{" " link "EditOkOk"}  Use
   @{" " link "EditCanc"}  Cancel

@endnode
@node "EditName" "The Edit Window - Name"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Name"}

This defines the name of the current file type. Do not define a name twice, because this could cause
problems with later versions.

@endnode
@node "EditClas" "The Edit Window - Class"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Class"}

@{b}This Gadget is only available during @{"expert mode" link "SETTExpe"}@{ub}@{par}

This Gadget allows to specify the type of the current file type. If you don´t find a match you
should use the type "User".@{par}

At the moment this class is used for output and sorting only. Please define this class correct to be
on the save side.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditSubC" "The Edit Window - Sub Class"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Sub Class"}

@{b}This Gadget is only available during @{"expert mode" link "SETTExpe"}@{ub}@{par}

This is the most important gadget. It specifies where to insert this file type.@{par}

A file detection only by name isn´t as save as a detection by the files contents.@{par}

This means a file detected by name only should be checked at the end of the list. Just think about a
lha file that is named "archive.c". This file may be interpreted as a c source if the sequence of a
file identifier is not correct.@{par}

   I defined some classes by name:@{par}

   User:             This class is used for user defined file types. You@{par}
                      should use one of the other types.@{par}
   Normal:           Under normal cases this is the best selection for@{par}
                      new cases.@{par}
   Medium:           This class is used for groups, (Kickstart - global,@{par}
                      Icon - global) because it doesn`t make any sense@{par}
                      to check a single Kickstart after a global definition.@{par}
   xxx or name:      e.g. "(FIND "<html>" OR NAME "#?.htm(l|)") AND ASCII"@{par}
                      This is better than "Name and ASCII", but not as good@{par}
                      as "Medium", because a file may not contain "<html>"!@{par}
   Name and ASCII:   This is reserved for file types that are only@{par}
                      identified by name and ASCII.@{par}
   Name only:        Checking a file by using only a name is one of the@{par}
                      worst methods, but sometimes there is no other@{par}
                      choice. So this is reserved for name only file@{par}
                      types.@{par}

@{b}Do not use the other classes, if not necessary.@{ub} If you create file types missing in AView
defaults, then please send me your the prefs file.@{par}

@{b}By the way:@{ub} It is possible to use the menu @{"open" link "MenuOpen"} function to load the
"Data/AView.data" file. This file contains all pre defined file types. Save this data by using the
menu @{"Save as" link "MenuSaveAs"}.@{par}

Be careful a wrong modification and AView isn`t working correct. Create a backup of this file before
changing it´s contents.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditExTy" "The Edit Window - Exec Type"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Exec Type"}

This Gadget allows to specify the way AView is starting the @{"command" link "EditComm"}. Under
normal conditions this is the CLI mode, but some programs may depends on a startup via Icon.

@endnode
@node "EditStac" "The Edit Window - Stack"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Stack"}

Each @{"command" link "EditComm"} needs an amount of stack memory. Normally 8192 Bytes should be
enough. If the program crashes increase this value.

@endnode
@node "EditComm" "The Edit Window - Command"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Command"}

If AView detects a known file type, it will start this command line. You should take a look on the
following % commands.@{par}

   %p  : includes the path of the file specified by @{"name" link "PATTNAME"}.(e.g "SYS:Pictures/")@{par}

   %~p : like %p! No "" this time.@{par}

   %n  : includes the file name of the file specified by @{"name" link "PATTNAME"}.@{par}
         (e.g "smurfs.gif")@{par}

   %~n : like %n! No "" this time.@{par}

   %f  : The complete file name of the file will be included.@{par}
         (e.g. "SYS:Pictures/Smurf.gif")@{par}

   %~f : like %f! No "" this time.@{par}

   %a  : This will be replaced by an @{"Arg" link "PATTARG"}. The default@{par}
          value may be modified by using the @{"Default %a" link "EditPreD"} Gadget.@{par}

   %~a : like %f! No "" this time.@{par}

There are only four command patterns (p,n,f,a). If you include a "~" after the % this means `insert
no ""`@{par}

@{b}If this command is processed during WB mode all % patterns will be removed. The only exclusion
is the %a (%~a) pattern.@{ub}@{par}

@{b}If you need a "%" in your command then use "%%"! AView replaces them to one "%"!@{ub}@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditCuTy" "The Edit Window - Current Type"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Current Type"}

This Gadget allows to specify a dos command feature that is called "Current Dir". It works like the
DOS-CD command.@{par}

   File directory  : Makes a CD to the path of the identified file.@{par}
   Current         : No Change!@{par}
   Specified Dir   : The Path is defined by the @{"CurrentDir" link "EditCuDi"} Gadget.@{par}

@endnode
@node "EditCuDi" "The Edit Window - Current Directory"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Current Directory"}

This Gadget is only available if the @{"Current Type" link "EditCuTy"} gadget is switched to
"specified directory"!

@endnode
@node "EditWBOu" "The Edit Window - WB Output File"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "WB Output File"}

Any Output of the @{"Command" link "EditComm"} will be directed to the file specified by this
gadget. This redirection is only valid if AView is running via workbench. (Double click on AView
icon or Toolmanager is starting AView in WB Mode)

@endnode
@node "EditCLIO" "The Edit Window - CLI Output File"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "CLI Output File"}

Any Output of the @{"Command" link "EditComm"} will be directed to the file specified by this
gadget. This redirection is only valid if AView is running via CLI.

@endnode
@node "EditIden" "The Edit Window - Identifier"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Identifier"}

@{b}This Gadget is only available during @{"expert mode" link "SETTExpe"}@{ub}@{par}

It a very important gadget. It is the heart of the AView file recognition system. This is done by
some @{"commands" link "COMMAND"}.

@endnode
@node "EditPreD" "The Edit Window - Default %a"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Default %a"}

This is the default for the @{"%a" link "EditComm"} pattern of the @{"command" link "EditComm"}
gadget. The contents of this gadget will be used, if no other argument is specified by the
@{"AView Dos Command" link "AView"}

@endnode
@node "EditOkOk" "The Edit Window - Use"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Use"}

All adjustments will be used.
@endnode
@node "EditCanc" "The Edit Window - Abort"
@toc "Edit"

@{MS "Abort"}

Cancels all adjustments and quit requester.
@endnode

@node "GeLW" "The File Type Selection"

@{MS "The File Type Selection"}

This window is viewing all default file types of @{"AView_Prefs" link "APMa"}.@{par}

This list is sorted by file classes, so it is easy to configurate AView.@{par}

Use the Cursor keys to select an entry and select via return key. You are also able to use the mouse
and double click to select.@{par}
@{code}
   @{" " link "GeLwOkOk"}  Use
   @{" " link "GeLwCanc"}  Cancel

@endnode
@node "GeLwOkOk" "The File Type Selection - Use"
@toc "GeLw"

@{MS "Use"}

The selected entry will be used.

@endnode
@node "GeLwCanc" "The File Type Selection - Abort"
@toc "GeLw"

@{MS "Abort"}

This gadget aborts the file type selection.
@endnode

@node "SETT" "The Settings of AViewPrefs"

@{MS "The Settings of AViewPrefs"}

It´s easier than it sounds. This window allows to modify some AViewPrefs internal Features. These
settings have no effect on AView.
@{code}

   @{" " link "SETTExpe"}  The expert mode
   @{" " link "SETTSave"}  Save
   @{" " link "SETTOkOk"}  Use
   @{" " link "SETTCanc"}  Abort
@endnode
@node "SETTExpe" "Gadget: Expert Mode"
@toc "SETT"

@{MS "Expert Mode"}

This gadget should be used by expert users only. It enables a special expert mode. This mode enables
hidden gadgets to make additional adjustments to your configuration.@{par}

@{b}You should understand the priority controlled file recognizing system and it is important that
you understand the main problem behind.@{ub}@{par}

For me the author it isn´t easy to find error in the pre defined file types. This means it won´t be
easy for you.@{par}

@endnode
@node "SETTSave" "Gadget: Save"
@toc "SETT"

@{MS "Save"}

All settings made in this window will be saved and this requester will be closed.

@endnode
@node "SETTOkOk" "Gadget: Use"
@toc "SETT"

@{MS "Use"}

The settings will be used.
@endnode
@node "SETTCanc" "Gadget: Abort"
@toc "SETT"

@{MS "Abort"}

The old settings will be restored.
@endnode

@node "Menu" "The menus of AViewPrefs"

{MS "The menus of AViewPrefs"}

These are the menu items of AViewPrefs:@{par}

@{b}Project@{ub}@{par}

   @{" " link "MenuOpen"}  Open...@{par}
   @{" " link "MenuSaveAs"}  SaveAs...@{par}
   @{" " link "MenuQuit"}  Quit@{par}

@{b}Default@{ub}@{par}

   @{" " link "MenuResetToDefault"}  Reset to Default@{par}
   @{" " link "MenuLastSaved"}  Last Saved@{par}
   @{" " link "MenuRestore"}  Restore@{par}

@{b}Preferences@{ub}@{par}

   @{" " link "MenuAViewPrefs"}  AView Prefs@{par}

@endnode
@node "MenuOpen" "Menu: Open"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "Open"}

This item allows to load a prefs file. @{b}The current settings will be lost!@{ub}

@endnode
@node "MenuSaveAs" "Menu: SaveAs"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "SaveAs"}

This item allows to save the prefs file.
@endnode
@node "MenuQuit" "Menu: Quit"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "Quit"}

Quit AView prefs and cancel all modifications.
@endnode
@node "MenuResetToDefault" "Menu: Reset to Default"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "Reset To Default"}

The file type list will be cleared a set to the default entries.
@endnode
@node "MenuLastSaved" "Menu: Last Saved"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "Last Saved"}

This menu point forces a reload of the last saved preferences.

@endnode
@node "MenuRestore" "Menu: Restore"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "Restore"}

This menu point forces a reload of the last used preferences.

@endnode
@node "MenuAViewPrefs" "Menu: AView Prefs"
@toc "Menu"

@{MS "AView Prefs"}

This menu will open the @{"AViewPrefs-preferences window" link "SETT"}.
@endnode

@node "FAQS" "Frequently ask Questions"

@{MS "Frequently ask Questions"}

   @{" " link "FAQStartProblem"} AView and AViewPrefs aren`t starting!@{par}
   @{" " link "FAQSpeed"} AViewPrefs sometimes is very slow.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQStartProblem" "AView and AViewPrefs aren`t starting"
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "AView and AViewPRefs aren`t starting"}

The OS2.1+ or OS3.0+ version of AView requires special catalog files. These files contain all text
information these programs need during operation. You will find the english catalog files in
"AView/Catalogs/english/AView.catalog".@{par}

It is not allowed to move a AView. This means after installing all file must stay on there place.
This is needed, because AView and AViewPrefs must be able to find special files like
"Data/AView.Data", "Prefs/AView.prefs" and so on.@{par}

@endnode
@node "FAQSpeed" "AViewPrefs sometimes is very slow."
@toc "FAQS"

@{MS "AViewPrefs sometimes is very slow."}

This is normal. AViewPrefs is sorting his data file and your preferences by name. The Sorting
procedure takes some seconds.@{par}

During the save operation AView is sorting you preference by @{"sub class" link "EditSubC"}. After
saving all entries are resorted by the mode specified in the @{"sort by" link "APMaSoBy"} gadget.
This is required because AView needs the settings sorted by @{"sub class" link "EditSubC"} to
process them correct. This procedure is better than let AView sort every time.@{par}

You are able to test the sorting speed by using the @{"expert mode" link "SETTExpe"}. This will
activate the @{"sort by" link "APMaSoBy"} gadget. Use the @{"all" link "APMaAlll"} gadget to see how
fast is your computer. (-8

@endnode

